The remaining question was the absolute configuration of C-25. Ganoderic acid A ( 4 ) is one of the major lanostane constituents in the medicinal mushroom Lingzhi (
G. lucidum
), and it is the first member of a large compound group with the trivial name. Therefore, it has been recognized as a symbolic
Ganoderma
lanostanoid. The structure of the C-20–C-27 side chain, possessing a C-23 ketone and a C-26 carboxylic acid, is one of the common features in
Ganoderma
lanostanoids. The absolute configurations of C-25 have not been determined for most of these compounds. Since the C-25 chiral carbon is isolated from the main part of the molecule, assignment of its configuration, relative to the tetracyclic ring and C-20, by NMR techniques is difficult. Additionally, the ECD calculation method would not be suitable for determining the relative configuration, while it is very useful for confirming the absolute configuration of the lanostane skeleton. There have been a few examples of the configuration of C-25 being determined by X-ray crystallographic analysis, and both 24 S - and 25 R -isomers have been reported (
;
;
). It is generally difficult to obtain crystals suitable for X-ray diffraction analysis for this group of compounds. For ganoderic acid A ( 4 ), most literature and web information (e.g., in catalogs as a biochemical reagent) do not show or indicate the 25 R configuration in the depicted chemical structure. We were unable to find literature that describes the determination of the C-25 configuration of ganoderic acid A, except for a recent US patent document that claimed to have a method for the determination of the configuration of ganoderic acid A by X-ray crystallographic analysis (Hsieh, 2019). However, the patent shows a 25 R -isomer in the ORTEP figure, but the 25 S -isomer is depicted as the presented chemical structure. More confusingly, the 1 H and 13 C NMR spectroscopic data (measured in CDCl 3 ) were apparently different from those reported in the original isolation report (
). NMR spectroscopic data (measured in CDCl 3 ) of compound 4 isolated in the present study from
G. sichuanense
were consistent with those of the original paper. The relative configuration, except for C-25, was confirmed by our own analysis of the 2D NMR spectroscopic data (similar to the structure elucidation of 1 as described above), which also led to the full assignments of protons and carbons ( Table S1 ).

Very recently, we reported the isolation of
Ganoderma
lanostanoids, ganoweberianic acids and ganoweberianones possessing the same type of side chain as ganoderic acid A (
) and determined the 25 S configuration for the most abundant compound, ganoweberianic acid A, by using the PGME method (
). Therefore, this method was also applied to ganoderic acid A ( 4 ). The Δ δ -values ( δ (S) – δ (R)) obtained from the ( S )- and ( R )-PGME amide derivatives 25a and 25b , respectively, indicated the 25 R configuration of compound 4 ( Fig. 4 ). Consequently, acetonide derivative 1 is also assigned as a 25 R -isomer. The methyl ester of 1 , named methyl ganoderate A acetonide, was previously isolated together with methyl ganoderate A (ganoderic acid A methyl ester) from
G. lucidum
, wherein the configuration of C-25 was not reported (
).

